## Where To Start

Read and edit these areas first:

- `{{ package_name }}/runtimes/` for transport-specific wiring and entrypoints
- `{{ package_name }}/features/` for business use cases and feature logic
- `{{ package_name }}/infra/` for technical adapters such as logging, database, Redis, or templating
- `{{ package_name }}/protocols/` for contracts between business logic and infrastructure
- `{{ package_name }}/models/` for shared business models

As a rule:

- put runtime code in `runtimes/`
- put business logic in `features/`
- put adapters and infrastructure wiring in `infra/`
- keep runtime-specific code out of business features when a protocol is enough

## Project Map

The generated project is intentionally small:

- `{{ package_name }}/runtimes/` contains runnable entrypoints and transport wiring
- `{{ package_name }}/features/` contains business capabilities
- `{{ package_name }}/infra/` contains infrastructure adapters
- `{{ package_name }}/protocols/` contains interfaces used across layers
- `{{ package_name }}/models/` contains shared business models
- `tests/` contains checks for the blocks included in this project

These packages are the fixed structure of the project.
The enabled blocks are placed into this structure.

## Enabled Blocks

{% if include_http_runtime %}
### HTTP Runtime

The HTTP runtime lives in `{{ package_name }}/runtimes/http/`.

It exposes:

- `GET /internal/healthcheck`
- `GET /internal/metrics`
{% if include_tg_bot_runtime and include_http_runtime %}
- `POST /telegram`
{% endif %}

Run it through the CLI:

```bash
uv run python -m {{ package_name }} http --reload
```

Use `APP_WORKERS_COUNT` to control uvicorn worker count in non-reload mode.
{% endif %}

{% if include_tg_bot_runtime and include_http_runtime %}
### Telegram Bot Component

The Telegram bot dispatcher and handlers live in `{{ package_name }}/runtimes/tg_bot/`.

Webhook updates are accepted by the HTTP runtime at `POST /telegram`.

Configure:

- `APP_TELEGRAM_BOT_TOKEN`
- `APP_TELEGRAM_WEBHOOK_URL`

The starter bot includes `/start`, `/ping`, and a small inline callback flow.
{% endif %}

{% if include_stream_runtime and include_redis_plugin %}
### Stream Runtime

The stream runtime lives in `{{ package_name }}/runtimes/stream/`.

It uses Redis as its broker transport and currently includes a simple ping subscriber.

Run it directly:

```bash
uv run python -m {{ package_name }} stream
```

Or expose its ASGI wrapper:

```bash
uv run uvicorn {{ package_name }}.runtimes.stream.app:build_asgi_app --factory
```

Configure:

- `APP_REDIS_URL`
- `APP_STREAM_PING_STREAM`
{% endif %}

{% if include_templating_component %}
### Templating Component

The templating adapter lives in `{{ package_name }}/infra/templating/`.

Its protocol lives in `{{ package_name }}/protocols/templating/`.

The sample template is:

- `{{ package_name }}/infra/templating/templates/greeting.jinja`

The generated renderer uses Jinja and exposes an async `render(...)` interface.
{% endif %}

{% if include_redis_plugin %}
### Redis Integration

Redis helpers live in `{{ package_name }}/infra/redis/`.

Redis-facing protocols live in `{{ package_name }}/protocols/redis/`.

Configure:

- `APP_REDIS_URL`
{% endif %}

{% if include_postgresql_plugin %}
### PostgreSQL Integration

Database code lives in `{{ package_name }}/infra/db/`.

Alembic migrations live in `alembic/`.

Configure:

- `APP_DB_HOST`
- `APP_DB_PORT`
- `APP_DB_NAME`
- `APP_DB_USER`
- `APP_DB_PASSWORD`
- `APP_DB_DRIVER`
- `APP_DB_DRIVER_SYNC`

Runtime access uses SQLAlchemy `AsyncSession`.
{% endif %}

{% if include_users_plugin and include_postgresql_plugin %}
### Users Feature

The ready-to-use users feature lives in `{{ package_name }}/features/users/`.

The shared user model lives in `{{ package_name }}/models/user.py`.

{% if include_http_runtime %}
The HTTP runtime also exposes:

- `GET /users`
- `GET /users/{user_id}`
- `POST /users`
{% endif %}
{% endif %}

